<span id="freeTextContainer8071943740379121673"><b>Erudite, sensual and bringing a lost Hellenistic world, or a pagan world transitioning to Christianity back</b><br/><i>For though his poems are not syntactically difficult or outwardly cryptic, thought they are therefore “available” to the average reader who comes to them without a panoply of scholarship, part of Cafavy’s modernity is that he does require this scholarship; perhaps it is simply his astonishing egocentricity, but he is saying in effect, my poems are me, and if you wish to read them the way th</i></span>
  <span id="freeText8071943740379121673" style="display:none"><b>Erudite, sensual and bringing a lost Hellenistic world, or a pagan world transitioning to Christianity back</b><br /><i>For though his poems are not syntactically difficult or outwardly cryptic, thought they are therefore “available” to the average reader who comes to them without a panoply of scholarship, part of Cafavy’s modernity is that he does require this scholarship; perhaps it is simply his astonishing egocentricity, but he is saying in effect, my poems are me, and if you wish to read them the way they should be read, you will have to know all about me, and that means knowing all about my life in Alexandria, and about my aristocratic ancestors, and my city’s glory and decline, and about other things that interest me.</i><br /><br />More thoughts to follow</span>
  <a data-text-id="8071943740379121673" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

