    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_424485671" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/424485671" />
    <a title="Peter Crofts" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12173625-peter-crofts"><img alt="Peter Crofts" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1345904368p2/12173625.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/424485671?book_show_action=true">Sep 29, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter Crofts" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter Crofts" href="/user/show/12173625-peter-crofts">Peter Crofts</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780375400964" href="/book/show/3775266-c-p-cavafy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer424485671" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17259600086720638403">I actually have the paperback edition of this volume which includes the unfinished poems as well. It&apos;s a good idea to go that route since many of the unfinished poems would seem to be pretty close to &quot;finished&quot;, or at least they read wonderfully.<br/><br/>Mendelsohn, the translator, needs to be praised on two fronts. Firstly as a translator he is sensitive to the subtlety of rhythm and rhyme with this poet. Cavafy is not unmusical, it&apos;s more that his musicality is minimal and austere. Second, the notes to</span>
  <span id="freeText17259600086720638403" style="display:none">I actually have the paperback edition of this volume which includes the unfinished poems as well. It's a good idea to go that route since many of the unfinished poems would seem to be pretty close to "finished", or at least they read wonderfully.<br /><br />Mendelsohn, the translator, needs to be praised on two fronts. Firstly as a translator he is sensitive to the subtlety of rhythm and rhyme with this poet. Cavafy is not unmusical, it's more that his musicality is minimal and austere. Second, the notes to this edition account for as much of the heft of the volume as the poems themselves, yet they do not interfere with your ability to encounter the poems for yourself. Rather the notes give lots of valuable and fascinating information concerning the vast number of historical figures who inhabit the poems.<br /><br />I've always felt uncomfortable approaching any artist based on their sexual orientation. I find it bizarre and frustrating that to many Cavafy is significant as one of the first openly gay poets. This is to the detriment to his work as a whole, which is certainly about desire but more so from the universal perspective of the passage of time. In fact I would say that the passage of time both in the historical and personal sense is his main theme.<br /><br />Certainly one of the best collection of poems I've read in a while. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17259600086720638403" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

