  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/55106146" />
    <a title="Jim Coughenour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/180643-jim-coughenour"><img alt="Jim Coughenour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535843128p2/180643.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/55106146?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim Coughenour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim Coughenour" href="/user/show/180643-jim-coughenour">Jim Coughenour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780375400964" href="/book/show/3775266-c-p-cavafy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/180643-jim-coughenour?shelf=reconditepoetry">reconditepoetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer55106146" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer915135940678847043">I first encountered Cavafy in the Rae Dalven edition back in the early 80s and immediately fell in love with him. No one has ever fused the poetic ache of eros, memory, sordid physicality and exalted historical consciousness as profoundly as Cavafy – a bookish, unattractive Greek homosexual living in Alexandria at the start of the 20th century. His simplest poems still leave me, sometimes, with a pain and wonder so deep I barely breathe – exactly as you feel when you remember someone you&apos;ve real</span>
  <span id="freeText915135940678847043" style="display:none">I first encountered Cavafy in the Rae Dalven edition back in the early 80s and immediately fell in love with him. No one has ever fused the poetic ache of eros, memory, sordid physicality and exalted historical consciousness as profoundly as Cavafy – a bookish, unattractive Greek homosexual living in Alexandria at the start of the 20th century. His simplest poems still leave me, sometimes, with a pain and wonder so deep I barely breathe – exactly as you feel when you remember someone you've really loved and really lost.<br /><br />Mendelsohn's translations are excellent (I own at least 4 other editions), but what sets his book high above the rest is his introduction and commentary. This is the most valuable book (along with its companion, Cavafy's <i>Unfinished Poems,</i> a different kind of miracle) that I've found this year. I apologize if this sounds like hype, or hyperventilating. But if you value poetry, these two books are irreplaceable. Even better, Knopf has produced them in handsome editions.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="915135940678847043" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


