<div id="review_3059091828" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3059091828" />
    <a title="Mark Joyce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42499758-mark-joyce"><img alt="Mark Joyce" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1479657688p2/42499758.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3059091828?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Joyce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Joyce" href="/user/show/42499758-mark-joyce">Mark Joyce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3059091828" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3941233989960182223">I’m not a wide reader of poetry and as such am possibly at risk of getting a bit carried away. Be that as it may, this (or, more accurately, the small “Selected Poems” anthology my wife bought for me on our favourite Greek island, which isn’t available for review on Goodreads) is among the best things I’ve ever read in any genre. I struggle to recall any writing that has moved me as profoundly as The City, The God Forsakes Antony, Ithaca and As Far As You Can, among others. The knowledge that Ca</span>
  <span id="freeText3941233989960182223" style="display:none">I’m not a wide reader of poetry and as such am possibly at risk of getting a bit carried away. Be that as it may, this (or, more accurately, the small “Selected Poems” anthology my wife bought for me on our favourite Greek island, which isn’t available for review on Goodreads) is among the best things I’ve ever read in any genre. I struggle to recall any writing that has moved me as profoundly as The City, The God Forsakes Antony, Ithaca and As Far As You Can, among others. The knowledge that Cavafy lived his life in almost total obscurity and wrote purely for a small circle of associates adds to the poems’ force and total authenticity. Simply (but also complexly) brilliant. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3941233989960182223" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


